   "source": [
    "# Variance Trading Game — Session 2 Demo\n",
    "## Northeastern University Options Club | September 30, 2026\n",
    "This notebook introduces the variance trading game: quote bid-ask spreads on the variance of card sums, watch uncertainty resolve as cards are revealed."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import sys\n",
    "sys.path.insert(0, '..')\n",
    "import matplotlib\n",
    "matplotlib.use('Agg')\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "from variance_dispersion import VarianceGame, GameConfig\n",
    "from variance_dispersion.estimator import BayesianVarianceEstimator\n",
    "print(\"variance-dispersion loaded\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 1. Run a Single Game\n",
    "Watch how true variance, Bayesian estimates, and uncertainty evolve as cards are revealed."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "config = GameConfig(n_players=4, n_hidden_per_player=2, n_community=6, seed=42)\n",
    "game = VarianceGame(config)\n",
    "state = game.reset()\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Cards per player: {config.n_hidden_per_player} hidden + {config.n_community / config.n_players:.0f} community\")\n",
    "print(f\"Total true variance: {state.true_variance_all_cards:.2f}\")\n",
    "print()\n",
    "print(f'{\"Round\":<6} {\"Revealed\":<12} {\"True Var\":<10} {\"Observed Var\":<14} {\"Est Mean\":<10} {\"Est CI\":<30}')\n",
    "print('-' * 75)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Player 0's estimate\n",
    "est = game.player_estimate(0, state)\n",
    "cv = f'({est.lower_95:.1f}, {est.upper_95:.1f})'\n",
    "obs_var_str = str(state.variance_observed) if state.variance_observed else 'N/A'\n",
    "print(f'{0:<6} {state.true_sum:<12.0f} {state.true_variance_all_cards:<10.2f} {obs_var_str:<14} {est.mean:<10.2f} {cv}')\n",
    "\n",
    "for i in range(config.n_community):\n",
    "    card = game.reveal_card(state)\n",
    "    est = game.player_estimate(0, state)\n",
    "    cv = f'({est.lower_95:.1f}, {est.upper_95:.1f})'\n",
    "    obs_var_str = str(state.variance_observed) if state.variance_observed else 'N/A'\n",
    "    print(f'{i+1:<6} {state.true_sum:<12.0f} {state.true_variance_all_cards:<10.2f} {obs_var_str:<14} {est.mean:<10.2f} {cv}')\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 2. Variance Converges to Truth\n",
    "As cards are revealed, the Bayesian confidence interval shrinks and the estimate converges toward true variance. This is the core mechanic: early quotes must be wide (uncertain), late quotes can be tight."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Re-run and track CI width evolution\n",
    "config2 = GameConfig(n_players=4, n_hidden_per_player=2, n_community=6, seed=123)\n",
    "game2 = VarianceGame(config2)\n",
    "state2 = game2.reset()\n",
    "\n",
    "ci_widths = []\n",
    "est_means = []\n",
    "true_vars = []\n",
    "\n",
    "# Initial\n",
    "for pid in range(4):\n",
    "    est = game2.player_estimate(pid, state2)\n",
    "    ci_widths.append(est.upper_95 - est.lower_95)\n",
    "    est_means.append(est.mean)\n",
    "\n",
    "# As cards revealed\n",
    "for _ in range(config2.n_community):\n",
    "    game2.reveal_card(state2)\n",
    "    for pid in range(4):\n",
    "        est = game2.player_estimate(pid, state2)\n",
    "        ci_widths.append(est.upper_95 - est.lower_95)\n",
    "        est_means.append(est.mean)\n",
    "\n",
    "true_vars = [state2.true_variance_all_cards] * len(ci_widths)\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(14, 5))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot 1: CI width shrinking\n",
    "xs = range(len(ci_widths))\n",
    "for pid in range(4):\n",
    "    p0 = slice(pid, len(ci_widths), 4)\n",
    "    axes[0].plot([i for i in xs][p0], [ci_widths[i] for i in p0],\n",
    "                 marker='o', markersize=3, linewidth=2,\n",
    "                 label=f'Player {pid}')\n",
    "axes[0].axhline(y=true_vars[0], color='red', linestyle='--', alpha=0.5)\n",
    "axes[0].set_title('Confidence Interval Width Shrinks')\n",
    "axes[0].set_xlabel('Round')\n",
    "axes[0].set_ylabel('CI Width (bid-ask spread analog)')\n",
    "axes[0].legend()\n",
    "axes[0].grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot 2: Estimate vs True\n",
    "for pid in range(4):\n",
    "    p0 = slice(pid, len(est_means), 4)\n",
    "    axes[1].plot([i for i in xs][p0], [est_means[i] for i in p0],\n",
    "                 marker='o', markersize=3, linewidth=2,\n",
    "                 label=f'Player {pid}')\n",
    "axes[1].axhline(y=true_vars[0], color='red', linestyle='--', alpha=0.5)\n",
    "axes[1].set_title('Variance Estimate Converges to Truth')\n",
    "axes[1].set_xlabel('Round')\n",
    "axes[1].set_ylabel('Estimated Variance')\n",
    "axes[1].legend()\n",
    "axes[1].grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.savefig('variance_convergence.png', dpi=150)\n",
    "print(\"Saved: variance_convergence.png\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 3. Key Insight: Non-Linearity of Variance\n",
    "\n",
    "Variance = E[(X - mu)^2] is a **non-linear** function of the data. Unlike the mean (which updates linearly), variance requires tracking both the mean AND the second moment.\n",n",
    "\n",
    "- **Early rounds:** Wide CIs because few observations → wide bid-ask → low profitability per quote\n",
    "- **Mid rounds:** CI narrows → can tighten quotes → profitable opportunity window\n",
    "- **Late rounds:** Near-certain variance → very tight spreads → thin margins, risk of stale quotes\n",
    "\n",
    "This is why variance market makers need different skills than mean market makers: they must update their variance estimate using Bayesian methods and understand that the optimal quote depends on BOTH the point estimate AND the confidence interval width."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 4. Key Takeaway\n",
    "The variance game builds intuition for why vol is mean-reverting:\n",
    "- Each new observation reduces uncertainty (shrinks CI)\n",
    - The optimal strategy is: WIDE early, TIGHT late\n",
    - Players who keep wide quotes too long lose flow; players who go tight too early get blown up\n",
    "\n",
    "In real markets, this maps directly to **VIX** and variance swaps. Market makers must calibrate spreads based on their Bayesian posterior uncertainty — not just the point estimate of realized variance."
   ]
  }
 ]
